ty (100 metric tons initially, growing to 200 tons). The disclosures highlight that *“delivering large amounts of mass to orbit at low cost will be critical to deploying AI compute satellites.”*  \n  Furthermore, the AI compute satellites themselves are evolved from the Starlink V3 satellite platform, leveraging existing satellite manufacturing, inter-satellite laser links, and on‑orbit operational experience (like automated collision avoidance). So Starlink’s proven technology serves as the foundation for AI compute, while Starship provides the necessary launch volume.\n\n- **Consequences of Starship Delays:**  \n  A Starship delay directly cascades into threats to both segments. The risk language warns that *“delays or challenges in the Starship program… would impede the expansion of our service offerings, defer anticipated revenue streams, and negatively impact our growth trajectory and competitive positioning.”*  \n  Without Starship, the deployment of V3 and orbital AI satellites stalls, and the company cannot achieve the lower cost‑per‑token or the petawatt‑scale AI constellation vision.\n\n### In Summary\nThe disclosure paints Starship as the **irreplaceable launch backbone** for both next‑gen Starlink and the orbital AI compute business. Starlink provides the satellite heritage and operational know‑how to build AI compute satellites, but Starship is the only vehicle able to lift them in volume. Any slip in Starship development directly jeopardizes the timeline and viability of these two major revenue‑generating initiatives, as explicitly stated in the risk factors.',
